library(dplyr)

The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

    date, intersect, setdiff, union
setDT(met)
#remove temperatures less than -17C, and making sure there is no missing data in the key variables coded as 9999, 999, etc. 
met <- met [temp > -17][elev == 9999.0, elev := NA]
#Generate a date variable using the funtions as.Date() (hint: you. will need the following to create a date paste (year, month,day,sep = "-"))
met[, week := week(as.Date(paste(year,month,day,sep = "-")))]
#using the data.table::week funtion, keep the observations of the firts week of the month. 
met <- met[week == min(week, na.rm = TRUE)]
#compute the mean by station of the variables temp,rh, wind.sp, vis.dist,dew.point,lat,lon,and elev.
met_avg <- met[,.(temp=mean(temp,na.rm=TRUE), rh=mean(rh,na.rm=TRUE),
                  wind.sp=mean(wind.sp,na.rm=TRUE),
                  vis.dist=mean(vis.dist,na.rm=TRUE),
                  dew.point=mean(dew.point,na.rm=TRUE),
                  lat=mean(lat), lon=mean(lon),
                  elev=mean(elev,na.rm=TRUE)), by="USAFID"]

#Create a region variable for NW, SW, NE, SE based on lon = -98.00 and lat = 39.71 degrees
met_avg$region <- ifelse(met_avg$lon > -98 & met_avg$lat > 39.71, "northeast",
                         ifelse(met_avg$lon > -98 &
                                  met_avg$lat < 39.71, "southeast",
                                ifelse(met_avg$lon < -98 & met_avg$lat > 39.71,
                                       "northwest", "southwest")))
#create a categorical variable for elevation as in the lecture slides 
met_avg$elev_cat <- ifelse(met_avg$elev > 252, "high", "low")

table(met_avg$region)

      484       146       649       296

5. Use geom_bar to create barplots of the weather stations by elevation category colored by region

met_avg %>%
  filter(!(elev_cat %in% NA)) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=elev_cat, fill=region), position = "dodge") +

Description:

the bar chart reveals significant differences in weather station distribution across regions and elevation categories. The southeast has the highest number of stations overall, particularly concentrated at low elevations. the region northeast shows more stations at high elevations compared to the rest. The northwest has the fewest total stations.

7. Make a map showing the spatial trend in relative humidity in the US

library(data.table)
library(leaflet)

#Make sure to remove NAs
met_avg2 <- met_avg[!is.na(rh)]

#use addMarkers to include the top 10 places in relative humidity (hint: this is a useful rank (-rh) <= 10)

top10 <- met_avg2[rank(-rh) <= 10]

rh_pal = colorNumeric(c('blue','purple','red'), domain=met_avg2$rh) #Make a color palette with custom colors

leaflet(met_avg2) %>% 
  addProviderTiles('OpenStreetMap') %>%
  addCircles (lat=~lat, lng=~lon, color=~rh_pal(rh),
              label=~paste0(round(rh,2), 'rh'), opacity=1, fillOpacity = 1, radius=500) %>%
  addMarkers(lat = ~lat, lng = ~lon, label = ~paste0(round(rh,2), 'rh'), data=top10) %>%
  addLegend('bottomleft', pal=rh_pal, values=met_avg2$rh,
            title="Relative humidity", opacity=1) #to add a legend

Description of the trend in RH across the U.S.

The relative humidity map reveals a clear concentrated gradient across the US. The east region show more relative humidity values (around 80-90%), represented by color pink or red colors, the central regions display lower humidity, while the western regions exhibit again higher values. the top 10 highest relative humidity locations predominantly located in states of Florida, California, South Dakota, and Kentoky which reflects the influence of the sea or rivers.

       fill = "Region") +
